SIMPLE: sedate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sedate
<hw>Se*date"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>sedatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>sedare</ets>, <ets>sedatum</ets>, to
allay, calm, causative of <ets>sedere</ets> to sit. See
<er>Sit</er>.]</ety> <def>Undisturbed by passion or caprice; calm;
tranquil; serene; not passionate or giddy; composed; staid; <as>as, a
<ex>sedate</ex> soul, mind, or temper</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Disputation carries away the mind from that calm and
<qex>sedate</qex> temper which is so necessary to contemplate truth.</q>
<rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whatsoever we feel and know⟦br⟧
Too <qex>sedate</qex> for outward show.</q>
<rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Settled; composed; calm; quiet; tranquil; still;
serene; unruffled; undisturbed; contemplative; sober; serious.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Se*date"ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Se*date"ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sedation</ent>⟦br⟧
